  "nursesNote": "Anger is a normal emotion; the problem is aggression, the harmful expression of anger through words or actions. The goal is to help the patient express anger in a healthy, assertive way (respectful 'I' statements) rather than aggressively or passively. The nurse recognizes early escalation cues (pacing, a louder voice, clenched fists, a tense posture) and intervenes early with a calm voice, respect for personal space, and offered choices, while encouraging the patient to name and talk through feelings before acting out. Teaching focuses on identifying triggers and using coping skills such as taking a time-out, physical activity, and relaxation. The nurse sets clear limits on behavior (not on the feeling itself) and protects safety, using medication or restraint only as a last resort.",
  "providerOrders": [
    "Recognize early signs of escalating anger",
    "Intervene early with a calm voice and offered choices",
    "Encourage the patient to verbalize feelings",
    "Teach triggers and coping skills (time-out, activity, relaxation)",
    "Set clear limits on behavior and ensure safety"
  ],
